
@startuml

' Define classes and their attributes
class Provider {
  - name: String
  - location: String
}

class Cruise {
  - cruiseNumber: String
  - name: String
  - startDate: Date
  - endDate: Date
  - destinationArea: String
  - seaName: String
  - ship: Ship
}

class Employee {
  - name: String
  - socialSecurityNumber: String
}

class Guest {
  - name: String
  - isVIP: Boolean
}

class Ship {
  - name: String
  - numberOfDecks: Integer
  - length: Double
  - numberOfPassengers: Integer
}

class Booking {
  - bookingNumber: String
  - bookingDate: Date
  - travelAgency: TravelAgency
}

class TravelAgency {
  - name: String
  - address: String
}

class Show {
  - title: String
  - duration: Integer
}

class Ticket {
  - ticketNumber: String
  - cruise: Cruise
  - guest: Guest
}

' Associations
Provider "1" -- "many" Cruise : provides
Cruise "1" -- "1" Ship : uses
Cruise "1" -- "many" Employee : has
Cruise "1" -- "many" Guest : has
Guest "1" -- "many" Ticket : has
Cruise "1" -- "many" Show : offers
Booking "1" -- "1" Cruise : books
Booking "1" -- "1" TravelAgency : made by
Ticket "1" -- "1" Cruise : belongs to
Ticket "1" -- "1" Guest : belongs to

@enduml

### Notes:
- This diagram represents all the entities, their attributes, and relationships as described in the system requirement.
- Relationships such as one-to-many or many-to-one are shown using appropriate notations (e.g., `1` to `many`, etc.).

